```cpp
#include <string>
#include <regex>

std::string markdown_to_html(std::string const& markdown) {
    // Define regular expression to replace markdown syntax with HTML
    std::regex re_md("(.*)\\\*\\*(.*)\\\*\\*/");
    std::regex re_bold("(.*)\\*\\*\\*?(?=[^*]|$)");
    std::regex re_italic("(.*)\\_\\*\\_*\\_\\*");
    std::regex re_href("\\[.*?\\]");

    // Replace markdown syntax with corresponding HTML tags
    std::string html = "";
    std::sregex_replace(markdown.begin(), markdown.end(), re_md,
                        [&](const std::smatch& m) { return "<strong>" + m[1] + "</strong>"; },
                        html);
    std::sregex_replace(markdown.begin(), markdown.end(), re_bold,
                        [&](const std::smatch& m) { return "<em>" + m[1] + "</em>"; },
                        html);
    std::sregex_replace(markdown.begin(), markdown.end(), re_italic,
                        [&](const std::smatch& m) { return "<i>" + m[1] + "</i>"; },
                        html);
    std::sregex_replace(markdown.begin(), markdown.end(), re_href,
                        [&](const std::smatch& m) { return "<a href=\"" + m[1] + "\">" + m[1] + "</a>"; },
                        html);

    // Replace multiple whitespaces with a single whitespace
    html = replace_all(html, " +", " ");

    return html;
}
```
`markdown_to_html()` function takes a reference to a `std::string` containing markdown formatted text as the input parameter and returns a `std::string` containing HTML formatted text as the output.

The function uses regular expressions to replace markdown syntax with corresponding HTML tags. The `sregex_replace()` function from the `<regex>` header is used to perform the replacements. The variables `re_md`, `re_bold`, `re_italic`, and `re_href` define the regular expressions used to match the markdown syntax. The replacement function uses a lambda function that takes the matched string from the regular expression and appends it to the `html` string produced by `sregex_replace()`.

The `replace_all()` function in the `string` header is used to replace multiple whitespaces with a single whitespace.

