To find the common elements in two arrays without using any extra data structures, you can implement a simple nested loop approach. Here's a sample Java program that does this:
```java
public class FindCommonElements {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] array1 = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
        int[] array2 = {3, 4, 5, 6, 7};

        int arr1Len = array1.length;
        int arr2Len = array2.length;

        for (int i = 0; i < arr1Len; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < arr2Len; j++) {
                if (array1[i] == array2[j]) {
                    System.out.println("Common element: " + array1[i]);
                    break;
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
```
In this program, we have defined two arrays, `array1` and `array2`, and two loops to iterate through each element of both arrays. Inside the loops, we perform a simple comparison to see if the current element in the outer loop is equal to the current element in the inner loop. If they match, we print the common element and break out of the inner loop to move on to the next element in the outer loop.

This solution does not use any extra data structures, so it runs in O(n^2) time complexity. However, it is still a self-consistent and polite way to solve the problem.
